      <p>
        <strong>Social Science Application.</strong>
        <a href="https://doi.org/10.1017/pan.2023.2" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Argyle et al. (2023)</a>
        demonstrated in <em>Political Analysis</em> that prompt framing
        and demographic "backstories" determine the distribution of
        simulated survey responses. The same survey question, posed with
        different persona prompts, produces different opinion distributions.
        This is the prompting-as-experimental-design argument applied to
        simulation: the prompt does not just extract information, it
        <em>constructs</em> the instrument. The same principle applies
        to the extraction and RAG pipelines in
        <a href="/course/day-4">Module 4</a>, where prompt design determines
